1":"1121","1099":"1099","1022":"1022","1020":"1020","1030":"1030","1040":"1040","1050":"1050","1060":"1060","1019":"1019","1028":"1028","0995":"0995","1124":"1124","1025":"1025","1101":"1101","1035":"1035","0980":"0980","Merionethshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Merionethshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Radnorshire, Wales":"Radnorshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Geza, Jeno, Arpad, Attila, Csaba.","Hungarian: variant of   Papp  , meaning ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’. This surname is also found in Romania, Slovakia, Croatia, and Serbia, and also among Rusyns (in Serbia and Croatia). See also   Pop   2 and   Popa  .","English: variant of   Pape   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Papp","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Laszlo, Zoltan, Geza, Istvan, Gabor, Miklos, Tibor, Arpad, Denes, Imre, Attila.","German (Bavaria, Tyrol): from Middle High German <i>pap</i> ‘baby food’, Dutch <i>pap</i> ‘porridge, pap’, hence perhaps a nickname denoting someone who had lost his teeth or subsisted on a meager diet.","Hungarian: from <i>pap</i> ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’, probably an occupational name for someone in the service of a priest or a nickname for a pious person. This surname is also found in Romania and Slovakia, and also among Rusyns. Compare   Pap   and   Pop  ."]}]},{"name":"Cadwgon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Welsh:  see  Cadogan  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cadogan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot.","Welsh (Pembrokeshire and Glamorgan) and Irish (of Welsh origin): from the Old Welsh personal name <i>Catgucaun</i>, <i>Catguocawn</i>, modernized as <i>Cadwgon</i>. It is composed of <i>cad</i> ‘battle’ + <i>gogawn</i> ‘honour, glory’. See also   Wogan  . The surname is stressed, like its Welsh original, on the penultimate syllable, hence its occasional development to   Duggan  .","Irish: from <b>Ó Ceadagáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Ceadagán</i>’."]}]},{"name":"Iorwerth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional: from <i>iōr</i>‘ ‘lord’ + a mutated form of <i>berth</i> ‘handsome’; borne in the <i>Mabinogi</i> by the jealous brother of  Madawg , son of  Maredudd . <i>Iorwerth</i> came to be regarded as a Welsh equivalent of  Edward , but it has no actual connection with that name."],"variants":[{"name":"Yorath","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Iorwerth   or, in some cases, a transferred use of the surname derived from it."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Iorwerth ap Cadwgon was born in 1030, in Wales, his father, Cadwgon ap Elystan Glodrydd, was 51 and his mother, Eva ferch Gwrgan of Glamorgan, was 35. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Gwenllian ARON."},"et":{"1030–":"1030–Surnud","1019–1050":"1019–1050","1020–Male":"1020–Surnud","1022–Male":"1022–Surnud","1025–1099":"1025–1099","1028–Female":"1028–Surnud","1030–Male":"1030–Surnud","1035–Female":"1035–Surnud","–1101":"–1101","1020–1121":"1020–1121","1040–1124":"1040–1124","1050–Female":"1050–Surnud","1060–Male":"1060–Surnud","0980–1066":"0980–1066","0995–1030":"0995–1030","about 1060":"umbes 1060","about 1040":"umbes 1040","1066":"1066","1121":"1121","1099":"1099","1022":"1022","1020":"1020","1030":"1030","1040":"1040","1050":"1050","1060":"1060","1019":"1019","1028":"1028","0995":"0995","1124":"1124","1025":"1025","1101":"1101","1035":"1035","0980":"0980","Merionethshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Merionethshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Radnorshire, Wales":"Radnorshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales"},"fi":{"1030–":"1030–Kuollut","1019–1050":"1019–1050","1020–Male":"1020–Kuollut","1022–Male":"1022–Kuollut","1025–1099":"1025–1099","1028–Female":"1028–Kuollut","10